title: For Sale/Trade:  18" .223 Wylde AR for sale
location: Camano island to Redmond, Everett, Washington
postcontent: I have a AR 15 chambered in .223 Wylde. For those that don't know, The .223 Wylde has the same chamber angling as the standard 5.56 chamber, so there’s no problem with pressures, and it also has a .2240 freebore diameter. The result? You have a chamber that is sufficient to handle the hotter 5.56 load without concerns about pressure and you get the gilt-edge accuracy that’s common in many quality .223 rifles. Is there a compelling reason to switch to a Wylde chamber? Well, the most obvious reason is that you can fire .223 ammo without giving up accuracy and 5.56 ammo without worrying about excess pressure. Sure, you can fire .223 ammo all day from a 5.56 without worrying about pressure problems thanks to generous chamber size, but if you really want to tighten those groups that .2240 freebore diameter helps. In fact, .223 Wylde chambers are known for extreme accuracy, which is better on the whole than what you can expect from a standard 5.56×45 chamber.There are so many parts from so many manufactures where it's hard to say it's this or that, but the lower was originally a stripped Del-ton lower, and the upper is a Aero percision upper. Everything has been replaced including the skeletonized 3.5 lb trigger, nickel boron BCG, fluded 18" .223 Wylde barrel, dust cover, take down pins, forward assist, bolt catch, MIGI muzzle break, charging handle, mag release, skeletonized grip, trigger guard, safety, hand guard, buffer tube, there's a lot that went into this rifle.

title: For Sale:  Winchester 1895 Carbine .30-40 Krag 22" 1915
postcontent: This auction is for the Winchester Model 1895 Carbine (with saddle ring) shown. Caliber is .30 Army (.30-40 Krag). The Model 1895 is a well constructed lever action rifle with an internal box magazine. The barrel length is 22". The S/N is 156780 indicating that it was made in 1915. The Model 1895 was made from 1896 until 1931. The overall condition of this rifle is very good to near excellent fro it's age. The rifle retains much of its original blued metal finish with only some light edge wear and light scratching with no brown tint. The magazine box and barrel band have a gray-brown patina. The plain walnut fore end and hand guard are very good with some marks from use, no cracks. The matching plain walnut butt stock is also very good, it shows some minor marks from use. The metal butt plate with trap is very good. The bore is very good, clean with well defined rifling with perhaps some light frosting in the grooves. The action is solid and smooth. Overall, a very nice and solid Winchester Model 1895 Carbine that is complete and in pretty nice condition.
